{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472383"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:57:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:57:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1290"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1290"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.77,0.03,0.06,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1290"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30604"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1290"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1290"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16547"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1865"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"11176"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"209"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/30604"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA neonate is being reviewed after the parents reported that the child was vomiting bile-stained fluid within the first few hours of life and had failed to pass meconium. The infant was diagnosed prenatally with Trisomy 21. On examination, prominent upper abdominal distension is noted. An abdominal X-ray is ordered which demonstrates the \u0027double bubble\u0027 sign.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pyloric stenosis","Duodenal atresia","Meconium ileus","Malrotation of the gut","Hirschsprung disease"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDown syndrome, or Trisomy 21, is a common congenital anomaly caused by the presence of extra genetic information from chromosome 21 in the human genome. The syndrome is associated with a number of gastrointestinal anomalies, most commonly \u003Cstrong\u003Eduodenal atresia\u003C/strong\u003E, and less frequently Hirschsprung disease and tracheo-oesophageal atresia. This neonate has the triad of features suggesting intestinal obstruction: bile-stained vomiting, failure to pass meconium, and abdominal distension. Differentials to consider in this case include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eduodenal and small bowel atresia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Evolvulus neonatorum\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Emalrotation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Emeconium ileus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHirschsprung disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuodenal atresia classically presents as bilious vomiting within the first few hours of life, with the characteristic \u0027double bubble\u0027 sign on abdominal ultrasound or X-ray. Duodenal atresia is associated with Trisomy 21, VACTERL, annular pancreas, and other intestinal atresias. Approximately 20-30% of infants with duodenal atresia have Trisomy 21.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The double bubble sign is pathognomonic of duodenal obstruction."],"references":["Stoll C, Dott B, Alembik Y, Roth M. Associated congenital anomalies among cases with Down syndrome. European Journal of Medical Genetics. 2015;58(12):674-680.","Bishop J, McCormick B, Johnson C, Miller J, Jelin E, Blakemore K et al. The Double Bubble Sign: Duodenal Atresia and Associated Genetic Etiologies. Fetal Diagnosis and Therapy. 2019;47(2):98-103."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16547"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1290"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/16547"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-12-05T21:46:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-12-05T21:46:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1290"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30604"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Grad